<|startoftext|>Headline:U.S. judge upholds Obama travel orders on U.S. citizens
Content: "(Reuters) - A U.S. judge in Hawaii on Thursday upheld an executive order issued by President Donald Trump that barred nationals of six other countries from traveling to the United States. U.S. District Judge Andrew Napolitano, in his order, said the administration may not take a new policy or even implement the order with respect to immigration applications and travelers, citing ongoing court cases involving refugees seeking to enter the country. Napolitano also ordered the Department of Homeland Security to review its constitutionality of Trump’s temporary travel ban on nationals of six other countries for national security reasons, a process that could take several months.  The Trump administration’s latest court order, issued in January, was one of a batch issued by the U.S. Homeland Security Secretary, the most prominent judge to challenge the measure. He was also temporarily banned from the United States, pending further review as well as the issuance of his order for a U.S. citizen to apply for naturalization. The department had appealed against Napolitano’s order that was issued last month in Maryland on Feb. 10, which it said was a “very clear public statement” of the federal government’s decision.  Napolitano’s decision will not take effect until further judicial proceedings have concluded, but he could issue a ruling on the merits of that appeal at the same time. ",<|endoftext|>
